<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (10): The prospects for economic recovery -
Interview: Professor Assar Lindbeck
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Assar Lindbeck is the head of the committee which chooses Nobel
Prize winners in economics. Earlier this year he headed the Lindbeck
Commission, which provided the government with the most detailed critique of
the country's economic and political problems for a generation. Proposing no
fewer than 113 reforms of the current system, the report mapped out a path
to economic recovery. Professor Lindbeck discussed the prospects for that
recovery with Christopher Brown-Humes:
Question: What is the short-term outlook for the economy?
Answer: I think we have bottomed out in all respects. Production and
manufacturing went down by 17 per cent from the top in 1989 to the bottom in
December 1992, but from January this year it has increased by about 8 per
cent. That reflects the dual economy. We have very high growth in the
manufacturing sector and exports but still falling domestic aggregate
demand.
What is still going down is building activity because that was blown up to
such a bubble during the 1980s. And municipalities are financially squeezed
and will continue to shed labour.
The crucial thing is what happens to private consumption because that is 55
per cent of GNP. The savings rate in the housing sector was minus 5 per cent
at the end of the 1980s; now it's plus 11 per cent. If this doesn't change
then the economy will continue to go down.
Will devaluation's gains be eroded as rapidly as they were in the 1980s?
There are some dramatic differences. In the 1980s unemployment never went
above 3.5 per cent; now it's 8 per cent, and 15 per cent if you include
those on training schemes. The other difference is that in the 80s you had
so many unique expansionary activities such as the building boom and the
deregulation of the capital markets. In the 80s you spoilt devaluation's
gains in five years between 1982 and 1987. They will probably last more than
five years this time.
What about the long-term development of Swedish competitiveness?
The social security system is being cut down to size. We suggested in the
report that benefit levels should not be higher than 70 or 80 per cent of
previous income. Now it is down to 80 per cent and there is a waiting period
before you get sick compensation. That has brought lower absenteeism. In the
late 1980s people were away from work with claimed sickness for 25 days a
year on average and if you include absenteeism for other reasons, like sick
relatives, it was 50 days.
Taxation of small firms is also being changed. Small firms play a much
smaller role in Sweden than in other European countries and when you look at
the tax system and regulation, you realise what an extraordinarily hostile
environment they have had for 25 years. That has changed dramatically.
To what extent has the public understood the change that has taken place?
People have been shocked by what has happened. They have found out that
Sweden was an ordinary country: we were not a planet outside the solar
system in its own orbit governed by laws legislated by labour unions and
labour market board.
The question is, do people believe it's just a temporary shock and you can
return to the old ways later on? I think many people do. The dilemma is that
55-60 per cent of the electorate get at least 80 per cent of their income
from the public sector. How do you reform the public sector when the
majority of the electorate live on tax money?
Today we have 137 tax-financed people for every 100 market-financed people.
Holland is worried because they have 70 tax-financed for every 100
market-financed. This explains the extraordinary tax burden and public
spending being 70 per cent of GNP. It also explains why you get such
enormous protests every time you try to cut something because you have
created these vested interests in public spending.
My advice to any country that is spending 40-50 of GNP in the public sector
is don't increase it because it's hopeless to get it down again. It needs
politicians with a suicidal instinct to take public spending down from 70 to
50 per cent of GNP. Anne Wibble (the Swedish finance minister) has such
suicidal instincts so from that point of view she's useful.
Is Sweden going to have to get used to unemployment at the levels we are
seeing now?
No, but we are not going to go down to the 1.5 per cent level we saw in
1989. Maybe we can get down to an open unemployment level of 3-4 per cent,
with a further 2 per cent on training schemes. But certain things have to be
done. Firstly, job security legislation has to be changed so that small
firms dare to hire. They don't dare to hire in a world of uncertainty
because it's too expensive to fire people. Secondly, future jobs have to be
created in the private services sector, which means reducing tax wedges.
The third factor is wages for low-skilled workers. In Sweden an 18-year-old
industrial worker has a salary which is 85 per cent of what a 34-year-old
earns, despite lacking skills, training and experience. It was only 55 per
cent 20 years ago. It has to go down to 55 per cent again, but it will be a
very painful process because it's against the ideology of the labour unions.
Is there scope for further cuts in interest rates?
Yes, for two reasons. One is that recession is so deep on the continent that
we have to expect cuts in interest rates there. Secondly, I think there is
some improvement in the budget deficit. The debt office reports a profound
improvement in the cash position of the government in the last three or four
months. That's important because many financial institutions were
forecasting a further deterioration of the budget deficit. I would think
lower rates were more likely than unchanged rates.
What is the outlook for the krona?
The exchange rate is undervalued in terms of competitiveness. But there are
still expectations of a further fall in the krona. How can that be? Because
people are not confident that Swedish politicians can control the deficit or
that the decisions so far have been credible enough. You have to be tough in
the sense that you make a credible commitment to solve the budget crisis
over a five-year period. On the other hand, you have to choose timing so
that you don't drive the economy down further.
How much inflationary pressure is there in the economy?
The risk for a new round of wage increases is modest when you have
unemployment of 8-15 per cent. Inflation went up from 2 to 5 per cent after
the devaluation, but now it's on the 2 per cent path again. But what happens
in the next upswing? Will wage earners try to get revenge? That's a risk,
particularly if people drop out from the labour force and cause bottlenecks
for skilled workers. You can get inflation problems even if unemployment is
6 per cent if the skill and regional mix is bad and you move too fast.
</TEXT>
