<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (9): Formidable twin challenge ahead -
Prime Minister Carl Bildt talks to Hugh Carnegy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The opinion polls are against him, but Mr Carl Bildt, prime minister,
appears to relish the formidable twin challenge facing him next year of
winning a general election and turning around public hostility to Sweden's
application to join the European Union.
As youthful and energetic as ever after two tough years in office, the
44-year-old leader of the Moderate Party (politically, the Moderates are
conservatives) insists it is possible to overcome the lowly image the EU has
taken on and repulse the offensive of the Social Democratic opposition in
spite of having presided over a painful recession that has driven
unemployment to levels unimaginable in Sweden a few years ago.
If he succeeds, Mr Bildt will have achieved his two principal political
goals: to lead Sweden politically, economically and irrevocably into the
heart of Europe and to complete the country's transformation from state
domination to an open, market-driven economy.
Mr Bildt's normally cheerful good temper has sometimes frayed as the
negotiations with the EU on an accession agreement approach a climax. Even
Sweden's greatest advocate of European integration bridles at examples of
'Brussels' interference in the way of life of ordinary Swedes' - such as the
EU's ban on 'snus', the orally-taken wet snuff that is so popular among
Swedes.
But he has soldiered on with his regular Monday campaign around the country,
trying to persuade a sceptical electorate that joining the EU is 'an
overriding national issue'.
'I feel a mood of great interest, especially among young people,' he said in
an interview. 'But they don't yet feel all their questions have been
answered.'
When the promised referendum on EU membership will be held is not yet clear.
So increasingly the more compelling public issue is next September's general
election, which current opinion polls suggest the Social Democrats will win.
But Mr Bildt firmly rejects the Social Democratic claim that the political
pendulum in Sweden is swinging away from his brand of liberal conservatism.
'They have said that for the past 15 years and they are wrong,' he retorts.
'They are the ones who are adjusting in our direction. They now talk about
the market economy in a way they would not have dared a couple of years ago.
'The overall direction of policy that we see in western Europe is very much
in the direction of further liberalisation; further deregulation of markets;
of opening up.'
He warms to the theme. 'In Sweden, I am, of course, radical and the Social
Democrats are the conservatives, bordering on reactionary. They are the
barons of the old order.
'They are resisting change much in the same way that in the mid-19th
century, which was a period in Sweden of very rapid liberalisation, you also
had the barons of the old order resisting change.'
He points out that in the 100 years to 1970, Sweden experienced growth
unmatched in the world, but that this ground to a halt in the next two
decades, a period in which the vaunted 'Swedish model' of industrial
welfarism reached its apogee.
'There was something fundamentally wrong with the policies that were pursued
during the 1970s and 1980s. I, of course, associate that with the dramatic
rise we had in the tax burden, with regulation and the role of public
expenditure in the economy. If that was part of the model it was a model
that clearly failed.
'We had enormous increases in transfer payments without increases in
production. We became the sickest society in Europe in terms of absentee
rates. We have seen during the past years productivity improving
dramatically - in the private sector primarily but now in the public sector
as well. We are becoming competitive now and with the changes under way
there should be an entirely new entrepreneurial climate in Sweden.'
The change in direction has been accompanied, however, by unemployment
approaching 14 per cent, an expensive banking crisis, a crash in house
prices, cuts in social benefits, a huge budget deficit and rapidly
escalating levels of government borrowing which combine to give the Social
Democrats considerable ammunition.
But Mr Bildt has so far skilfully managed his minority coalition with the
Liberal, Centre and Christian Democratic parties, keeping the government
united without a single cabinet change since it took office in late 1991.
Now, he says, the pay-off is beginning to show through.
'When we started off I said our aim was to get growth rates back to those in
comparable European countries by the mid-1990s - we haven't been there for
25 years - and to create the conditions for having growth rates well above
the European average by the latter part of the century. That is perfectly
feasible if we continue our policies.'
The question is whether the electorate will vote for more of the Bildt
prescription, which has proved so painful for so many.
'The mood of the country is a realistic one,' he says, adding that his
government is less unpopular now than the previous Social Democratic
administration was at an equivalent stage.
'The difference is, we will have a situation where the economy is seen to be
improving. So I am always saying that I will be surprised if we don't have a
non-socialist majority after the elections. The margins are very tight -
much tighter than most people realise.'
</TEXT>
