<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (7): Mood of profound scepticism - Sweden
and the European Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As many Mondays as he can, Mr Carl Bildt, Sweden's prime minister, heads off
to various towns and villages around the country to drum up support for
Swedish membership of the European Union. Judging by the latest opinion
polls, he might well think his time could be better spent.
Swedes, like their Nordic neighbours in Finland and Norway, are profoundly
sceptical about European Union membership, and if anything their opposition
has increased as 1993 has progressed.
The mood suggests the pro-EU lobby is going to have to fight all the way to
make Swedish accession a reality by the targeted date of January 1 1995. The
very least that will be required for a 'yes' vote in next year's referendum
is a successful outcome to the entry negotiations, and that is still by no
means guaranteed.
Recent opinion polls have given the anti-EU camp 45-48 per cent support and
those backing membership a mere 26-30 per cent. The No vote may have slipped
a little from its peak, but the last time that more people were in favour of
membership than against it was in March 1992.
Although business and leading politicians broadly support the EU, many other
groups in society are largely opposed to it, including women, young people
and blue collar workers. In addition there are deep splits within a number
of political parties. The leaders of the Social Democrats, the Centre Party
and the Christian Democrats, which all support membership, are to a greater
or lesser extent out of line with their membership, who are against.
Internal EU disarray over matters such as Maastricht, unemployment and
Yugoslavia has undoubtedly complicated the task of those seeking to get to
Sweden into the union. But many Swedes seem to have deep-seated emotional
reasons for their opposition: they implicitly link the EU with the wider
process of change which has brought deep cuts to the welfare state and a
sharp rise in unemployment.
They also have a strong sense of pride in a system which, notwithstanding
the difficulties of the past three years, has brought the country tremendous
economic success over the past 50 years. They do not want to head into the
unknown and risk a wholesale dismantling of that system if they can no see
no tangible benefits from EU membership in return.
That is part of the problem. Sweden is due to join the European Economic
Area (EEA) alongside other European Free Trade Association (Efta) countries
on January 1 1994, and in doing so will become part of a barrier-free
trading region which stretches from the Arctic to the Mediterranean. Why go
further and sign up for the EU? For all that politicians stress that Sweden
will gain more influence, most Swedes worry that they will simply get more
interference.
The feedback from the negotiations, which began in February of this year,
has done much to encourage this view.
Swedish politicians have time and again accused the European Commission of
being insensitive on 'Nordic' questions such as wet snuff and alcohol
policy. The Commission has indicated it would like to ban wet snuff, known
in Sweden as 'snus', and scrap the Nordic countries' monopoly on alcohol
imports and distribution. But one in 10 Swedes is a regular snuff-taker, and
the country has a strong temperance lobby.
It is not surprising, therefore, that there have been warnings of a backlash
against Brussels' interference in Sweden's domestic policies and traditions
 -and fears that if the Commission does not give way, the referendum will be
lost.
In many ways these 'symbolic' issues have come to assume greater importance
in Sweden than matters such as agriculture and regional policy, to which
Finland and Norway have given greater weight. Environmental policy also
falls into this category, the worry being that public opinion will be
negatively influenced if Sweden is forced to lower its standards.
Aside from such concerns, it is apparent that Sweden is becoming worried
that it will be unable to complete its negotiations by the EU deadline of
March 1, endangering the whole accession timetable.
Mr Ulf Dinkelspiel, minister for European affairs and foreign trade, was
irked by the sluggish pace of talks when he spoke to journalists recently,
saying that difficulties over snuff and free trade agreements with the
Baltics should already have been resolved. He was looking for substantial
progress ahead of a EU ministerial meeting scheduled for today. Even if such
progress is made, the timetable is tight. Several important questions have
still to be discussed including agriculture, regional policy and budget
contributions - and they could all prove difficult.
The big unresolved question is when exactly Sweden will hold its referendum
on the EU. Three alternatives have been canvassed by the government: next
June, three months after the negotiations should have been concluded and
before the summer holidays; next September on the same day as the general
election; or during the autumn. All three choices have their drawbacks. The
Social Democrats, who may well form the next government, clearly disfavour
June or September, and in any case it will be difficult to swing opinion in
favour of membership before then. By waiting until next autumn, however,
momentum will be lost and the newly-elected government will almost certainly
be preoccupied with internal and domestic matters.
The Social Democrats, who actually lodged the Swedish application back in
1991, are commonly seen as the key to a Swedish EU entry on the grounds that
without their active campaigning there is little chance of the country being
won over. A comparison is made with Denmark, which only voted in favour of
Maastricht at the second attempt after a change of government which brought
the Social Democrats to power.
The trouble is that the Swedish Social Democrats are deeply split over the
EU and they have certainly not mobilised the party faithful to promote a Yes
vote so far. On the contrary, the party has preferred to lie low, awaiting
the outcome of the negotiations. Whether Sweden does eventually join the EU
will depend very much on the line the Social Democrats adopt once the result
of those discussions is known.
</TEXT>
