<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (8): Bridge still awaits go-ahead - Link
with Denmark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When PLM, the Swedish international packaging group with its headquarters in
Malmo, calls together managers from its 13 European plants, they usually
meet in Copenhagen, on the Danish side of the narrow straits which separates
Sweden from Denmark at the entrance to the Baltic.
The managers fly into Copenhagen's Kastrup international airport, but to get
from there to Malmo by hovercraft connection - which the weather sometimes
prevents - adds about 90 minutes to the journey, allowing for waiting time,
says Mr Per Erlandsson, head of corporate communications. For this reason
alone, PLM, like most of the companies in southern Sweden, will welcome the
day when the planned road-and-rail bridge across the Oresund is completed,
cutting travel time between Kastrup and Malmo to about 30 minutes.
Sweden and Denmark have signed a treaty by which the two states are
committed to building the bridge and the governments have set up a joint
consortium, Oresundskonsortiet, to plan, finance and act as main contractor
for the project. It will cost about DKr19bn, including the on-land
investments on the Danish and Swedish sides of the link. Construction should
begin in 1994, although political obstacles to the final decision to go
ahead have yet to be resolved.
Sweden's Centre Party, headed by Mr Olaf Johansson, minister for the
environment, is opposed to the bridge, for environmental reasons.
If the government decides to give the go-ahead to construction - Mr Carl
Bildt, the prime minister, has said that he hopes the decision can be taken
before the end of the year - there will be pressure from the party
organisation for the Centre Party to withdraw from the government.
Perhaps it is not entirely coincidental that the Centre Party is the Swedish
party which is least enthusiastic - although not completely set against -
Sweden's membership of the European Union. For, as Mr Erlandsson says, the
bridge also has an important symbolic value: 'It will show that Sweden wants
to get closer to Europe.'
Geographers on both sides of the Oresund, meanwhile, are in little doubt
that the bridge will be of enormous significance for southern Sweden and the
Copenhagen area.
'The bridge will, without question, revitalise industry and the regional
workforce' in Scania (the province of southern Sweden) and Sjflland (the
large Danish island on which Copenhagen is sited), wrote* Professor Lars
Nordstrom, transport economist from Chlamers Technical University,
Gothenburg.
Musing over the controversies which surround the bridge at present, he
suggested that in the long term the bridge would bind Malmo and Copenhagen
together so closely that it would appear odd that the bridge once did not
exist. And if something should happen to the bridge, it would be regarded by
future generations as a catastrophe.
As things stand, Copenhagen and Malmo might as well be hundreds of
kilometres from each other, not just the 18km which in fact is all that
separates them, says Professor Christian Wichmann Mathiessen of Copenhagen
University, a Danish geographer who is one of the more visionary enthusiasts
of the bridge.
The city regions on either side of the sound are 'completely separate
systems', he says, pointing to surveys which suggest that for every personal
contact between residents on the two sides of the sound there are 16
contacts between residents of southern Sweden and Stockholm.
The Oresund, according to Professor Mathiessen, is one of the world's great
traffic junctions: the land traffic junction between Sweden and continental
Europe; an important shipping lane; and the site of one of northern Europe's
largest airports, Kastrup.
Within a radius of 50km of Kastrup there is a population of 2.3m people,
making it the 20th-largest city region in Europe. Copenhagen - the
population of the greater Copenhagen area is about 1.3m - ranks as the
32nd-largest and Malmo - population 235,000 - is 140th. In terms of
purchasing power, the Oresund region ranks as eighth in Europe.
The region is already an important area for scientific research, but could
become even more so if the scientific communities on the two sides of the
sound were to become more integrated. In terms of research capacity,
Copenhagen ranks 12th in Europe; Malmo and the university town of Lund rank
30th. Together, the region ranks fourth or fifth in Europe for its research
capacity.
On the Swedish side, Astra, the pharmaceuticals giant, Gambro,
medical-technical products, Tetra Pak Alfa Laval, food industry machinery,
and Kockums, the shipyard specialising in submarines, are among the
companies which give Malmo and Lund a high-technology profile.
Once the bridge is built, the separate systems will begin to change. 'The
sound area will rapidly shift from the old balance situation with two
separate systems which both function well, into a system with a new balance,
characterised by new movements of people, merchandise, services,
information, energy and money,' says Professor Mathiessen. But it will not
happen on its own. 'It all depends on local mobilisation. The future market
should be shining bright for the population, politicians and administrators
and business leaders. What is needed is action, local action.'
In Malmo they agree. 'The bridge alone won't do it,' says Mr Dag Fagring,
city promotion manager, although the bridge will help by focusing attention
on the city. He has just put forward a SKr6m promotion programme, Advantage
Malmo, to try to persuade business, Swedish as well as international, that
Malmo is a good place to be, and, with the bridge in prospect, getting
better all the time.
*Quotations from Professors Nordstrom and Mathiessen are from Oresund -
Past, Present and Future (Essays on the Oresund region), published by
Coronoa AB, Malmo 1993)
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
    DKZ  Denmark, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
