<PROFILE>_AN-DLUC5AFYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (6): Pension system is a time bomb -
Welfare
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sweden's huge welfare state - built up during the booming years of the 1950s
and 1960s - is under enormous strain.
The demands of people on the social security system based on universalist
principles of provision have grown dramatically in recent years while
economic growth has stagnated.
More than 60 per cent of Sweden's gross domestic product is accounted for by
the needs of the public sector,the highest proportion of any country in the
world and a substantial part of it is accounted for by social expenditure
after debt repayments.
Swedes have been talking about the cost 'crisis' of their welfare state for
nearly 10 years. It was in 1986 that the LO blue-collar union federation
pronounced at its congress that public expenditure should not grow any
higher as a percentage of gross domestic product in order to meet the needs
of the citizen.
The ruling Social Democrats at the time said they were determined to improve
the productive efficiency of the existing welfare system. There was a new
emphasis on consumer choice to break down the rigidities of state services
that were over-bureaucratic.
Some market-oriented Social Democrats began to argue that society and the
state were no longer synonymous and people should be encouraged to take more
responsibility for their own well-being.
But their commitment to reform was still tempered by a desire to uphold the
principle of equality of access for all to the welfare state through
universalistic programmes.
However, the twin pressures of rising consumer demands on increasingly
limited resources and accelerating costs in a stagnant economy forced more
radical discussion across the political spectrum by the early 1990s.
An attack by Sweden's vociferous band of neo-liberals has made little
progress among the policy makers. Even inside the ruling Moderate party,
social conservatives seem to be much more influential than their economic
liberally minded colleagues when it comes to discussions on the welfare
state.
Mr Bengt Westerberg, minister of social affairs and leader of the Liberal
party, remains an eloquent champion of the verities of the Swedish system
and it is hard to see any frontal assault against the welfare state
succeeding with him in the cabinet.
The two other parties in the coalition government - the Centre and the
Christian Democrats - are strong believers in the Swedish way of social
provision. Security and caring remain key words in the language of
contemporary Swedish politics.
Any political leader who campaigned to tear down the existing system in the
name of individual freedom would suffer severe defeat at the polls.
But this does not mean that a drastic shake-up will not come in the very
near future to public services that used to be the envy of the world.
The return of mass unemployment to Sweden has brought a new and added cost
burden to the welfare state that seems likely to grow over the next few
years adding to the size of the public sector deficit.
Over the past three years successive governments have been forced by the
demands of the global economy to trim around the edges of welfare spending.
There have been cuts in sickness benefit entitlements, for example, despite
often stiff domestic resistance from the powerful public sector interest
groups. More fundamental reforms are also being planned, especially for the
provision of health care.
In September last year, agreement was reached in principle between all the
main political parties in a crisis package designed to defend the fixed
exchange rate of the krona to take both sickness and work injury insurance
out of the state budget and put its funding and administration in the hands
of the social partners-employers and unions.
It was suggested this move could come from the mid-1990s but the
implications of such a radical change remain unclear.
Many conservatives believe this would pave the way for the rapid growth of
private insurance schemes to replace the state system. Social Democrats see
the move as a sensible way of providing a new and enhanced role for the
trade unions. The future of the pension system is a time bomb ticking away
at the heart of the Swedish welfare state as Swedes grow older and the
existing means of financing pensions becomes increasingly difficult to
sustain.
The scope for more private and occupational pension schemes seems likely to
grow as the state provision fails to ensure the country's pensioners
maintain a reasonable standard of living.
</TEXT>
