<PROFILE>_AN-DLUC5AFXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (2): Recession appears to be ending - The
economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The longest and deepest recession Sweden has suffered since before the
Second World War appears, at last, to be ending. 'The signs that we see seem
to indicate that the recovery is there - and slightly better than we
thought. It is time we had some good news,' said Mrs Anne Wibble, the
finance minister who has had the unenviable task of steering the economy
through the hard times.
The upturn will not show up in this year's overall growth figure. The
government's estimate for 1993 is that gross domestic product has contracted
by 2.8 per cent, much sharper than the successive retreats of 1.7 per cent
in each of 1991 and 1992. But the trends show that the economy hit bottom
around mid-year and has since been edging upwards.
Industrial production, fuelled by a resurgence of export growth, has risen
this year by approaching 2 per cent after a fall of 3 per cent last year. In
1994, the government predicts gross domestic product growth of 2 per cent.
The scars of recession, however, will take much longer to heal and, with an
election looming next September, the political debate over the appropriate
structure for Sweden's economy for the remainder of the century is
sharpening.
As the country moves tentatively out of recession it is carrying some heavy
burdens. The budget deficit stands at more than 13 per cent of GDP and is
set to rise higher - to an estimated 15 per cent of GDP in the 1993-94
budget year. This has pushed up central government debt from about SKr600bn
in 1990 to more than SKr1,000bn, or about 70 per cent of GDP, inevitably
stacking up a heavy repayment schedule for the future.
Above all, the recession has seen a leap in unemployment unprecedented in
Sweden, which until the late 1980s saw itself as having created the elusive
formula of combining a strong welfare state with virtual full employment. In
1989, 'open' unemployment - excluding those on government training schemes -
stood at less than 2 per cent of the workforce. Today, open unemployment is
more than 8.5 per cent, with a further 5 per cent of the workforce on
training schemes.
In confronting what to do about unemployment, policymakers face a striking
contrast between the external and internal sectors.
What growth has been rekindled in the economy has come largely from export
industries which have benefited hugely from the 25 per cent fall in the
value of the Swedish krona that followed the flotation of the currency in
November 1992. Exports are set to rise 6 per cent this year and a further 9
per cent next year, moving the current account balance into surplus.
But the domestic economy, the engine of significant employment creation, has
remained mired in recession. Government curbs on the public sector have been
partly responsible. The centre-right coalition has taken SKr77bn out of the
budget over the past two years and plans to extract a further SKr80bn over
the next four years, mostly through lower public spending.
However, a dramatic shift in savings patterns by the public has also had a
profound effect. The removal of generous tax breaks on debt interest,
collapsing house prices, rising unemployment and general uncertainty about
future prosperity have provoked a wave of debt consolidation and saving. The
household sector savings ratio has swung from minus 5 per cent to plus 11
per cent of income in just a few years.
The result has been a sharp contraction of private consumption, by 2 per
cent in 1992 and more than 5 per cent this year. This is significant because
private consumption makes up 55 per cent of GDP.
Mrs Wibble hopes there will be a small recovery in private consumption next
year, fuelled by interest rates that have fallen to about 5 per cent. But
the best most economists expect is about 1 per cent growth. On top of that
outlook, net investment in the economy is still falling - by 10 per cent
this year - and is not expected to recover until 1995.
The gloomy state of the domestic economy has prompted the opposition Social
Democratic party to insist that there must be a stimulus to demand to help
generate growth, suggesting cuts in VAT and delays in increases in other
indirect taxes.
'We fear that domestic demand will not lift the economy next year,' says Mr
Goran Persson, the Social Democratic shadow finance minister. 'We think for
1994 we need to stimulate the economy. If we don't there is a danger of a
downward spiral to depression.'
Mrs Wibble and the centre-right government are anxious to lower taxes as
part of their commitment to a market-driven economy. This year, they have
made room for removing tax on dividends. But for now, Mrs Wibble says,
reducing the budget deficit must have priority.
'We are not going to introduce any fiscal stimulus because it would have the
opposite effect,' she says. 'The strategy is to keep on with fiscal
consolidation as planned and to make it possible to keep on with the
stimulus from monetary policy. That will be much more effective.'
The political conflict over economic policy has been ill-received in the
markets, contributing to the weakness of the krona. Until earlier this year,
the Social Democrats had co-operated with the government. There was broad
political acceptance of a benchmark study of the economy produced by a
commission led by Professor Assar Lindbeck which made no less than 113
recommendations in general aimed at liberalisation and reducing the state's
role in the economy.
The Social Democrats continue to accept that the public sector, which in
1992 amounted to 70 per cent of GDP, had become too large to sustain.
Mr Persson says a Social Democratic government would continue the battle
against the deficit and seek to promote private industrial growth. But he
opposes the government's belief that the frontiers of the state should be
rolled much further back, as soon as the state of the public finances allow,
through greater tax reform and more private involvement, for example in the
service sector.
The Social Democratic commitment is to get the deficit in check so that they
can bolster, not reduce, the welfare state. 'There are areas that should not
be deregulated - which the market cannot handle,' Mr Persson says. 'Our
policy relies on having strong public finances because without strong public
finances you cannot have a strong welfare state.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
