<PROFILE>_AN-DLUC5AFVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (4): Time to tighten belts - Unemployment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The rapid return of mass unemployment to Sweden over the past three years
has come as a profound shock to a country that has not known lengthy dole
queues since the Great Depression of the early 1930s.
Last month, 357,000 Swedes were registered without a job; some 8.4 per cent
of the workforce. Total employment has dropped by as much as 9 per cent
since the start of the recession at the end of 1990.
All the forecasts - both official and independent - suggest it will be at
least the second half of next year before the jobless total stops growing.
But there is no prospect of any radical improvement in labour market
conditions for the foreseeable future.
However, the country's comprehensive and well-funded labour market
programmes of training and placement are expected to keep the actual level
of open unemployment down below the European Union average. Last month, as
many as 220,000 Swedes were covered by those measures; 5.1 per cent of the
workforce. The government's existing plans provide for a total of 400,000
people being offered a job or training and education in the current
financial year.
The Swedish Labour Market Board, in its recently published forecasts for the
rest of the century, suggests the combined total number of unemployed and
those on a labour market scheme will still amount to more than 11 per cent
of the workforce.
Such a grim outlook is regarded as unacceptable to many Swedes. Even during
the recessions of the mid-1970s and early 1980s, the country was able to
avoid soaring unemployment unlike much of the rest of the western
industrialised world.
However, Sweden's policy-makers accept privately that it will be very
difficult to restore 'full' employment. 'Work for all' used to be the
inspiring slogan that successive Swedish governments carried out in
practice. But not even the most committed of Social Democrats can really
guarantee delivering such an objective.
Mr Bildt's government insists that 'In the long term there is no other way
to increase employment in Sweden than by pursuing a policy which helps to
strengthen and maintain the country in a competitive position and
sustainable low inflation and thus lower interest rates'.
Ministers rule out monetary and fiscal expansion to cut unemployment.
Instead, they emphasise the need for structural changes in the labour market
by making it easier for employers to hire and fire; the removal of rules and
regulations that they see as obstacles to job creation; and moderation in
wage demands.
Few in Sweden believe the country can reverse the current spiralling trend
of joblessness on its own and there is a widespread acceptance that its
employment prospects depend on the development of a wider European strategy.
Mr Allan Larsson, the former Social Democratic finance minister, presented
an interesting commissioned paper on employment earlier this month in
Brussels that won the approval of all the European Social Democrats,
including the British Labour party.
In flavour and substance it is not far removed from the policy document
presented by Mr Jacques Delors, European Commission president, at this
month's EU summit. The emphasis is on the need to combine competitiveness
with solidarity.
In the past, Sweden's Social Democrats used the country's public sector as
the main engine for job creation. But Mr Larsson's document rules out any
further expansion there. Instead, the emphasis is on creating economic
conditions which will enable medium and small-sized private entrepreneurs to
hire workers while training and vocational training are given a prominent
place in the jobs strategy.
Mr Larsson's approach calls for 'a strategy of investment-led growth' as
'the only fair and sustainable route to sound public finances'.
It seems unlikely - unless there is a dramatic surge to the left in the
German federal elections next December - that Mr Larsson's strategy will be
practised by EU member state governments. But it may be used by the
left-wing parties in next June's European parliamentary elections and
provide the basis for his own party's economic programme in office if they
win next September's Swedish general election.
The Labour Market Board is not being starved of funds to administer measures
to keep a substantial number of people out of the unemployment figures.
These measures include some imaginative ideas targeted on workers without a
job for three months or longer - such as recruitment subsidies for employers
to employ them; educational leave replacement; working life development
enabling workers to leave their jobs for a period to be replaced by the
jobless; relief work as well as workplace introduction; and youth training
schemes to help the 18- to 25-year-olds.
But the labour market programmes cannot provide opportunities for all the
unemployed. Increasingly, financial resources are being deployed - as a
proportion of total spending - into income maintenance for the unemployed
and not to labour market measures. Last year, SKr24.07bn was spent on
benefit payments to the unemployed and this year the figure will climb to
more than SKr50bn.
The present government has reduced the maximum benefit available to the
jobless from 90 per cent to 80 per cent of previous earnings to a level of
SKr564 a day for a maximum of 300 days.
The unemployed have to be gainfully employed for at least 75 days over a
12-month period to qualify for the insurance benefit. Since September, they
have had to wait five days before the benefit is paid and the benefit can be
terminated if a worker refuses 'suitable work' or behaves in an anti-social
way that contributes to them not being employed.
The Swedish government has aroused opposition in the labour movement with
its proposal to reform the existing unemployment insurance system with the
introduction of a payroll tax of 1 per cent from January and 2 per cent in
1995 to help fund it.
The government also wants to introduce a voluntary insurance scheme which
would supplement or run in parallel with the existing system but this is
seen as an attempt to weaken trade union involvement in the administration
of the benefit. What all sides have yet to accept is that the soaring cost
of unemployment is adding to Sweden's mounting budget deficit. The
unemployment insurance fund is well into debt at more than SKr50bn and the
state is having to borrow on the money markets at competitive interest rates
to sustain the present levels of employment benefit.
It is hard to see how this can continue indefinitely. Like it or not, Sweden
is going to have to tighten its belt and accept that its still relatively
generous approach to dealing with unemployment will have to change. This
will prove a severe test, however, for the strong social consensus that has
lasted for more than 50 years.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
