<DOCNO>FT934-1039</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DLUC5AFUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Survey of Sweden (1): Year of opportunities ahead - Next
September, Swedes will vote in a general election. Some time in 1994 they
will also decide whether or not to join the European Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sweden, a country once so confident of its destiny, is facing a new year
full of challenges and choices.
After three years of recession, in which the economy has shrunk by more than
5 per cent, a return to modest growth seems likely in 1994. But the pace of
recovery and, above all, a reversal of unemployment now running at about 14
per cent of the workforce, will depend greatly on the extent to which there
is a rekindling of confidence in the still slumbering domestic economy.
In September next year, Swedes will vote in a general election. They will
select either the vigorous market reform policies of prime minister Carl
Bildt's right-centre coalition or a return to the leadership of the Social
Democratic Party, with its commitment to preserve the essentials of the
welfare state it constructed over the past 30 years.
During the course of 1994, Sweden will also decide whether or not it should
join the European Union. Negotiations on accession are scheduled to be
completed by March 1. If the timetable is stuck to, the issue will be put to
a referendum by the end of next year.
As 1993 draws to a close, the pointers do not look, at first sight, very
encouraging for Mr Bildt and his conservative Moderate party. Opinion polls
have given the Social Democrats more than 50 per cent support. They also
show a persistent hostility towards joining the EU, despite support for
membership from the leading government and opposition parties.
Other issues have been interpreted as showing that Swedes are not responding
to Mr Bildt's impassioned call for a reformed Sweden to become a full and
enthusiastic participant in the development of a more integrated Europe.
Early this month, the senior management and shareholders of Volvo, the
country's biggest and best-loved manufacturer, staged an unprecedented
rebellion against a plan to merge the company's car and truck operations
with state-owned Renault of France. The main opposition was concerned with
the structure of the deal - but it also attracted an emotional objection to
a foreign takeover that bodes ill for those campaigning for EU membership.
Sweden's environmentalists, with the support of the coalition-member Centre
Party and apparently many voters, are meanwhile trying to block plans agreed
with Denmark to build a road and rail bridge from the southern city of
Malmo, across the narrow Oresund, to Copenhagen.
Mr Bildt, however, gives no impression of being down-hearted. He believes
that there is a broad acceptance in Sweden of policies designed to cut back
the role of the state in the economy, despite the pain of recession.
Confident of a 'robust recovery' over the next two years, Mr Bildt says
conditions in the economy will be improving perceptibly by the time the
election is held, sufficient to ensure another non-socialist majority in the
Riksdag (parliament). Then, the intention is to build on the steps already
taken to reduce public spending - through measures such as cuts in
unemployment and sickness benefits - and to open up the state-dominated
service sector to private business. The public sector in Sweden still
accounts for close to 70 per cent of gross domestic product.
'What remains is to bring down the overall level of taxation - in terms of
social costs and VAT,' says Mr Bildt. 'Public consumption is going down
faster than expected, but of course much remains to be done, particularly in
the public health sector. On the budget deficit, a robust recovery is going
to do quite a lot, but not enough.'
The prime minister admits, however, that he is concerned about the appetite
for more liberalisation among an electorate which long ago grew accustomed
to the generous levels of state welfare afforded by the 'Swedish model'. 'I
am afraid that when the economy starts to do better, a lot of people are
going to ask 'Well, do you need these policies of reform any longer?'' he
says.
This is what the Social Democrats are out to exploit. The party is by no
means advocating a complete return to the policies of the past. It
acknowledges that the balance between public and private sector in Sweden
became unsustainable. It was the Social Democrats who, when last in office,
launched reforms to cut the country's previously huge income tax burden.
But, under the leadership of former prime minister Ingvar Carlsson, the
Social Democrats are firmly committed to retaining the essentials of the
welfare state. The party emphasises the need to foster private sector
industrial growth but opposes steps taken by the present government such as
the abolition of taxes on dividends.
'I don't think the problem is the public sector,' says Mr Carlsson. 'Really
the problem today is that we have such low demand. You can say that it is
because there is such insecurity in the public sector - people don't know
what will happen to their state pensions, or what will happen when they are
unemployed - that people now save much more. One of the best stimulations of
the economy today would be if we create some kind of clarification about the
social securities.'
The intensifying election battle has considerably complicated the issue of
Sweden's application to join the European Union. Although it was the Social
Democrats who, in a break with traditional party policies, lodged the
application in 1991, there are deep divisions in approach to the question
between the opposition and Mr Bildt.
The Moderates see membership as essential for Sweden's future economic
prosperity, but they also see it as a means to shift Sweden decisively away
from its previously aloof strategic stance. In the post-cold war world, they
want to place Sweden at the centre of the EU's political, economic and
strategic development.
Mr Bildt says the logic of Swedish neutrality 'has gone' and instead Sweden
should help bring a 'northern perspective' to the development of western
Europe's strategic and defence policy.
The Social Democrats, meanwhile, are deeply split over EU membership. A
majority of their supporters oppose joining, not least because many are
still strongly attached to neutrality. The thrust of Mr Carlsson's advocacy
of membership concentrates on the perceived benefits Sweden could gain from
wider policy co-operation in the fight against unemployment.
With opinion polls showing support for membership at little more than 25 per
cent, and opposition around 45 per cent, it is clear to all sides that
winning approval for membership in the promised referendum will require
changing opinion within the Social Democrats.
This makes choosing a date for the referendum extremely difficult. Assuming
the negotiations on an accession agreement are completed, the government
would ideally favour a vote in June, or simultaneously with the general
election. But the Social Democratic leadership does not want to have to try
to persuade a sceptical party to support a 'Yes' campaign at the same as it
is fighting an election.
Mr Carlsson wants to wait until after the election. 'We must prove to the
people that we can solve their daily problems better inside the EU than
outside. That takes time and if we lose this referendum it will take 10 or
20 years before it can be brought up again,' he says.
Mr Bildt fears, however, that the 'No' campaign, led mainly at present by
marginal left-wing and environmental groups, will gain in strength the
longer it has to organise. It is one of the circles he must try to square in
1994.
</TEXT>
