<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow drifts to slightly firmer
close
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US blue chip stocks inched ahead yesterday while the wider market edged
lower in subdued pre-holiday trading, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 3.64 higher at 3,755.21,
while the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 eased 0.53 to 465.85. In the secondary
markets, the American SE composite was off 0.12 at 464.08, but the Nasdaq
composite firmed 0.92 to 760.15. NYSE volume came to 256m shares.
Stocks opened lower but quickly reversed course in a pattern that typifies
trading on Monday mornings following 'triple witching days', when the
quarterly expiration of options and futures contracts generates heavy volume
and exaggerates underlying market trends. On Friday the Dow industrials
gained 25.43 at 3,751.57.
However, with no fresh macro-economic news due until later in the week,
investors yesterday were left adrift, with only the listless bond market to
offer guidance.
Activity in US Treasuries was subdued ahead of today's keenly awaited
meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, in which the policy-making
panel was expected to adopt a bias towards tighter money, shifting from its
current stance of neutrality. In late trading, the benchmark 30-year
government bond was  5/16 lower at 99 9/32 , yielding 6.298 per cent.
Blue chips, which were ahead 8 points at mid-morning, meandered in and out
of negative territory most of the day, before closing with a slight gain.
However, some cyclical issues, which should benefit most from improved
economic conditions, were strong. Goodyear Tire added Dollars 5/8 at Dollars
44, Cummins Engine Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 51 3/4 , Caterpillar Dollars 1
1/4 at Dollars 87 5/8 and Tennaco Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 52 1/8 .
Allied Signal edged up Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 77 1/2 even though the stock
was downgraded by Oppenheimer. Union Carbide put on Dollars  7/8 at Dollars
22 1/4 . CPC International, the agricultural products company, was 1 3/8
higher at Dollars 47 3/4 after CS First Boston raised its rating to 'buy'
from 'hold'.
IBM fell Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 58 1/4 on the announcement that technical
problems would delay delivery of updated versions of its PS/2 personal
computer models.
In banking stocks, Wells Fargo climbed Dollars 3 5/8 to Dollars 128 3/4
after Brown Brothers Harriman boosted its estimate of the company's 1994
earnings.
Borden was marked up Dollars 5/8 to Dollars 18 5/8 on reports that its
directors were considering a plan to sell the ailing food and chemicals
company, either as a whole or in parts.
On the Amex, US Bioscience dropped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 9 1/4 on concern
that the US Food and Drug Administration would delay action on approving its
Ethyol ovarian cancer medication.
Canada
In spite of a rise in gold and other mining issues, Toronto ended flat as
the market came under pressure from tax-loss selling. Investors are making
use of the federal capital gains exemption for fear of it being scrapped in
February's budget.
The TSE 300 index was just 0.06 up at 4,223.6. Volume came to 59.3m shares
and falls outscored rises by 464 to 382.
The mining and gold indices rose 1.4 and 1.1 per cent respectively. The
transportation group had the day's biggest fall, 1.7 per cent.
</TEXT>
