<DATE>931221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / International Company News: Earnings at Nike plunge 30% to
Dollars 52.3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nike, the US maker of athletic shoes and sports wear, yesterday confirmed
the gloomy trend in its financial performance by reporting a 30 per cent
fall in net income to Dollars 52.3m from Dollars 76m in its second quarter
to November 30.
Mr Philip Knight, chairman, delivered a robust defence of the company's
strategy and said he was optimistic about next year's autumn back-to-school
season and beyond. 'We remain the best-positioned company in the industry to
grow as we enter fiscal 1995,' he said
Nike, which warned in September that this financial year's figures would
fall short of 1992-93 levels, has been suffering from a shift in purchasers'
tastes away from basketball and other sports shoes towards the rugged
footwear made by companies such as Timberland and Dr Martens.
Sales in the latest quarter fell by 8 per cent to Dollars 805.8m from
Dollars 875.8m, and net income per share fell by 30 per cent to 69 cents
from 98 cents. For the six months to date, net income was down to Dollars
166.4m from Dollars 198.6m.
Nike said adverse shifts in exchange rates were partly to blame for the
fall. On a constant dollar basis, it said, revenues would have been down by
only 1 per cent and net income per share would have been 77 cents.
Looking ahead, the company said worldwide orders for footwear and apparel
for delivery between December and next April were Dollars 1.4bn, some 14 per
cent below the comparable period. But Mr Knight said these figures disguised
the reasons for optimism.
Nike had a significant and growing share in the US market for rugged
casuals, Mr Knight, but its solid advances in this sector had been
overshadowed by a 25 per cent decline in its revenues from basketball shoes,
a sector that had been experiencing 'the ebb and flow common in this
industry between individual categories'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Nike Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
