FT  21 DEC 93 / International Company News: Paramount receives fresh
takeover bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Viacom, the cable television company, and QVC Network, the television
shopping business, both submitted fresh takeover offers yesterday to
Paramount Communications, the entertainment company which has put itself up
for auction.
Paramount did not disclose the value of the two proposals submitted by the
4pm deadline that had been set for bidders' best offers, but said that the
board would evaluate each of them.
Late in the afternoon QVC said its plan to announce the value of its bid had
been blocked by the Securities and Exchange Commission, which oversees the
securities industry.
It added that it was still negotiating with the SEC and might be able to
announce the offer later in the day. Viacom declined to comment on whether
it would reveal its bid.
The Paramount board is expected to meet today to review the bids and will
eventually recommend one of them, though shareholders will be free to accept
whichever one they choose.
Before last night's developments, QVC had a bid on the table worth around
Dollars 10bn and Viacom one of Dollars 9.6bn.
Just 24 hours before the deadline Mr Sumner Redstone, chairman of Viacom,
issued a strong defence of controversial purchases of his company's stock in
recent months - some by a private company he owns and some by an investment
firm in which he holds a stake.
Mr Redstone's statement appeared designed to reassure the board of Paramount
and Wall Street of the value of Viacom's stock, which is likely to form part
of the company's revised bid.
There has been speculation in the US media that the share purchases could
have helped bolster Viacom's share price.
Viacom said, however, that 'rather than inflating the price of Viacom
securities, the more legitimate inquiry is whether the repeated, inaccurate
and misinformed publication of rumours and innuendo has served the agenda of
QVC by damaging the reputation of Viacom's management and by artificially
damaging the market price of Viacom stock.'
It added that investments in Viacom by Mr Redstone's private company,
National Amusements, had taken place in the period preceding the announced
merger with Viacom and were part of a well-publicised market purchase
programme which had been in effect for six years.
</TEXT>
