<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Bank moves to ease money market difficulties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England is proposing to broaden the scope of its money market
operations to help overcome the liquidity problems which have dogged the
City since Black Wednesday.
The proposed changes, involving the sale and repurchase of UK government
bonds, should reduce the volatility of short-term interest rates. Overnight
rates have ranged from about 4.5 per cent to well over 10 per cent,
according to the Bank.
The new arrangements could pave the way for an 'open repo' system for gilts,
enabling investors to lend their holdings in the same way that holders of US
Treasury, French and German government debt can do. The Bank plans to
introduce the new arrangements in early 1994.
Following the crisis in September 1992 when the Bank had to intervene
heavily to support sterling, the money market has suffered from a lack of
liquidity. The Bank was forced to introduce temporary facilities to provide
liquidity to the banking system, allowing the ad hoc sale and repurchase of
gilts.
'The scale of the Bank's money market operations has remained large and it
seems likely that facilities of the kind provided since September 1992 will
continue to be needed for the foreseeable future. The Bank proposes
therefore to make them a systematic component of its money market
operations,' says the central bank in its document.
The Bank has decided to make these repo facilities available on a regular
fortnightly timetable, with funds provided through the purchase and resale
of UK government debt denominated in sterling or other currencies. It also
proposes to widen the range of participants to allow all banks, building
societies and gilt-edged marketmakers (Gemms) to act as counterparties.
Previously, only the top banks and building societies, as well as the Gemms,
were allowed to do so.
'This move will dramatically reduce the volatility of the overnight interest
rates,' said a money market specialist at a big clearing bank. Banks should
have a much clearer idea of their short-term funding costs as a result.
</TEXT>
<XX>
