<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Russia breaches diamond deal with De Beers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Russian government, desperate for hard currency, is selling uncut gem
diamonds from its Treasury stockpile directly to dealers in Antwerp in clear
breach of its agreement with De Beers, the South African group which
controls more than 80 per cent of the world's rough, or uncut, diamond
market.
Between Dollars 40m and Dollars 80m of diamonds had been 'leaked' to the
west in the past two weeks, Mr Gary Ralfe, a De Beers director, suggested
yesterday.
The Russian problem emerged at the end of a record year for the Central
Selling Organisation, De Beers' London-based offshoot that organises the
international diamond cartel. The CSO reported yesterday that its rough
diamond sales reached Dollars 4.355bn (Pounds 2.91bn) in 1993, 28 per cent
higher than last year's total and 5 per cent above the previous record in
1988.
The former Soviet Union re-joined the diamond cartel in 1990, giving the CSO
exclusive rights to sell 95 per cent of its production for five years. At
the same time, De Beers advanced the government a Dollars 1bn loan and
shipped some of the Soviet diamond stockpiles to London as collateral. After
the break-up of the Soviet Union, Russia agreed to continue the accord.
The international diamond market relies on De Beers to even out the peaks
and troughs in demand via the cartel - a system it calls single-channel
marketing.
Mr Ralfe said he had made it clear during a meeting with a senior Russian
official at the weekend that any large-scale leakage of gem diamonds would
destabilise the diamond market. 'I urged the Russians not to damage the
long-term benefits of single-channel marketing for short-term gain,' said Mr
Ralfe.
The official - whom Mr Ralfe refused to identify - said great care was being
taken not to undermine the market and said the diamonds were not not being
sold at cut prices.
Mr Ralfe said the sale of a second category of rough diamonds, from Russia's
strategic defence stockpile, had been 'worrisome' for De Beers this year.
These stones were outside the marketing deal because at the time they were
stockpiled they were non-gems for industrial and technical use. However,
many had now been cut in India where an ability to polish, economically,
very small stones, has been developed over the past 20 years.
The US was also selling diamonds from its strategic stockpile and this was
causing 'some signs of oversupply in the lower and cheaper quality range of
rough diamonds,' said Mr Ralfe.
Diamond sales record, Page 22
</TEXT>
