<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Channel 4 is a British network with London headquarters. London is one of
the world's great capital cities: its earliest buildings stood on the banks
of the Thames before the Romans arrived. Thousands of plays, films and
programmes have been made about London. So what do you suppose is the
linking theme for Channel 4's special Christmas season? That's right - New
York.
They begin with Tall Stories (7.50), a short documentary about New York
skyscrapers. At 10.00 comes RuPaul's Christmas Ball, RuPaul Charles being a
black American drag queen and 'chanteuse'. Channel 4 asserts that 'his
appearances on American chat shows have made him a household name'. Not in
your house, perhaps, or mine, but in those of Channel 4 executives no doubt.
11.05 brings the first of four programmes looking at New York's 24-hour
cable news service and that is followed by Straight Out Of Brooklyn (11.35)
a movie about lives of violence and poverty in New York. Do you often find
yourself with friends lamenting the paucity of American material on
television?
</TEXT>
