<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Big electricity users back down in dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pressure on Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity regulator, to
reach a compromise with generators National Power and PowerGen increased
yesterday when big energy users backed down from their insistence that the
generators should be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The Major Energy Users' Council said that there was no need for a referral
if changes were made to the way prices were determined in the wholesale
electricity pool.
Mr Peter Rost, chairman, said: 'This offers an escape route from a
monopolies inquiry, which would involve delay and uncertainty.' He wanted
the government to use the coming sale of its 40 per cent stake in the
generators to create additional companies in the market.
Prof Littlechild said last week that he would decide on a reference by
mid-January.
The change of stance from the council is significant because the
organisation represents influential organisations including Marks and
Spencer and the National Health Service.
Its preference for a negotiated settlement over pool prices means that
virtually all interested parties have expressed a desire for referral to be
avoided.
The council's policy shift follows its commissioning of a report, by Ilex
Associates, the consultancy, which was published yesterday. Ilex concludes
that the generators' rates of return are 'arguably higher' than appropriate
when there is surplus capacity but are not excessive.
It suggests the pool-price determination should be changed so that it
reflects more accurately the costs of generation. In part this would be
achieved by increasing capacity-related payments.
Greater variation between peak and off-peak prices would result.
Ilex says the regulator could bring about such change but would have to
regulate the pool-price bidding system. The objective would be to 'curb
National Power's and PowerGen's ability to gain excessive profits through
their manipulation of pool prices'.
Ilex says prices for household consumers would increase only marginally by
0.06p per kilowatt hour but those for base-load industrial customers could
fall 0.3p per kwh on average in the middle of the decade.
Industrial prices in the UK electricity market. Ilex Associates, 104
Gloucester Green, Oxford, OX1 2RH. Pounds 950 plus VAT.
</TEXT>
