<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Ministry to review defence purchasing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Changes in the way the Ministry of Defence handles arms purchases and
training are being considered in an effort to save hundreds of millions of
pounds on the annual defence budget from 1996.
The targets of the review range from financial management and computer
systems to recruitment and promotional activities - including showpieces
such as the RAF's Red Arrows and the army's parachute display team.
The ministry aims to save money by scrapping some of the security
precautions set up during the cold war and reducing the number of people
subjected to 'positive vetting'.
Officials have identified 15 areas for examination by specialised teams
under the defence-cost study announced after the November Budget.
The study is aimed at helping the ministry save about Pounds 1bn in its
annual spending from the 1996-97 financial year without damaging
effectiveness.
The drastic nature of the cuts means that ideas previously regarded as
'out-of-bounds' are likely to be included in initial proposals put to
ministers in three or four months. One official said the question now was:
'Which sacred cows will have to be shot?'
The biggest savings are expected to come from procurement, where options are
being considered for leasing, acquisition of second-hand vehicles and other
equipment, increased competition in collaborative international projects and
greater use of private-sector finance.
Officials will seek to draw lessons from close scrutiny of several large
projects, such as the proposed new Anglo-French-Italian frigate.
Significant economies are expected in repairs, spares supply, storage and
freight, possibly though private contractors. Manufacturers may be required
to provide in-service support for the equipment they supply.
Training is also seen as a source of big savings, particularly in RAF flying
instruction - the initial stage of which is already privatised - and the
army. A review of property management is likely to lead to the sale of some
of the more commercially attractive pieces of ministry property.
Also under investigation are the ministry's head office and procurement
staff, together employing about 8,000, and the 5,000-strong ministry police.
</TEXT>
<XX>
