<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Treasury to repay Ecu5bn loan ahead of its final maturity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury is to repay, ahead of its final maturity, an Ecu5bn seven-year
revolving bank credit that was arranged in September last year to help
support the pound against severe foreign exchange pressure, Tracy Corrigan
writes.
The move reflects the recovery in the level of the UK's foreign-exchange
reserves since the events surrounding Black Wednesday last year.
Tranches of the credit, which is currently fully drawn, will be repaid
successively over the next four months, at respective roll-over dates. The
repayment will come from foreign currency resources. Some Ecu3.5bn will be
financed from forward purchases of foreign exchange set aside for the
purpose; the rest will be drawn from foreign-exchange reserves.
Foreign-exchange and gold reserves stood at Dollars 43.6bn at the end of
November, and are expected to rise further in 1994 with issues under the
three-year Ecu Treasury note programme.
</TEXT>
