<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Current account deficit lowest for two years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The current account deficit in the third quarter was the lowest for two
years, on the back of a healthy surplus on earnings from financial services
and relatively fast growth in merchandise exports.
The deficit came to Pounds 1.613bn, after Pounds 2.348bn in the second
quarter. Between July and September, Britain had a surplus on invisible
trade - services, profits and dividends and other financial transfers - of
Pounds 777m compared with Pounds 708m in the previous quarter.
The invisibles surplus offset the difference between merchandise imports and
exports - the visible trade gap - in the third quarter. This was a
relatively low Pounds 2.39bn, after Pounds 3.056bn in the second
three-monthly period.
In the first nine months of the year the current account deficit came to a
seasonally adjusted Pounds 6.644bn after Pounds 8.547bn in the whole of last
year. In its Budget forecast last month the Treasury said the current
account deficit for 1993 would be Pounds 9.5bn.
The current account deficit in the third quarter was covered by a surplus on
Britain's capital account, helped by record purchases of UK government gilts
by overseas groups.
In the third quarter Britain had a Pounds 2.974bn surplus on trade with
other countries in financial services including banking and insurance,
compared with a surplus of Pounds 2.543bn in the second quarter.
This large excess of exports to imports in this sector of the services
industry offset deficits in other services - for instance the travel trade
saw a Pounds 904m deficit in the third quarter and civil aviation a deficit
of Pounds 117m.
Britain earned a surplus of Pounds 1.037bn on interest, profits and
dividends in the third quarter, after Pounds 876m in the second quarter.
There was, however, a Pounds 1.663bn deficit on general financial transfers
 -also part of the invisibles account - in the latest three-monthly period
after Pounds 1.166bn between April and June. Much of this deficit was due to
a large net payment of Pounds 1.595bn from the UK to overseas government
institutions, mainly the European Union, in the latest quarter.
</TEXT>
