<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Openness on lottery bids allowed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Applicants for the licence to run the UK's multi-billion-pound National
Lottery will be able to make as much information about their bids public as
they wish.
The move to potentially greater openness represents a change of heart by Mr
Peter Davis, director-general of the National Lottery.
Last month's draft rules set out rigid conditions of confidentiality for all
applicants.
The draft documents said they would 'be required formally to agree' that
neither they nor the director-general would be allowed to publish anything
but the names and addresses of applicants without the approval of the other.
Mr Davis originally said he thought that both press and public risked being
'confused' by the release of incomplete information. He has changed his mind
after considering a number of submissions arguing for greater openness.
Mr Richard Branson, the Virgin Group chairman bidding on the understanding
that all profits will go to a charitable foundation, said there was a duty
to publish details of a bid and its strengths.
It is believed that when the licence conditions are published today they
will give the freedom Mr Branson and others asked for.
At least eight groups have said they will apply, or are seriously
considering applying.
Meanwhile, Mr Des Wilson of Mr Branson's UK Lottery Foundation declined to
give details of how the group planned to raise the multi-million finance it
would need without an equity base. He said only that talks with a bank were
nearing completion
</TEXT>
