<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / BCCI 'presented false accounts for a decade'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A small group of trusted officials at Bank of Credit and Commerce
International presented false accounts over nearly a decade to deceive the
government of Abu Dhabi over how its money was being used, the government's
lawyers said yesterday.
Several senior executives in BCCI's headquarters in Leadenhall Street,
London, and in ICIC, a subsidiary in the Cayman Islands, fabricated
valuation statements of Abu Dhabi's money while spending the cash to prop up
the loss-making bank.
The details of their claim emerged from a briefing by lawyers at Simmons &amp;
Simmons, a London-based firm of solicitors, as they announced a Dollars 7bn
civil case against 13 former executives of the bank in Abu Dhabi.
From November 1980 to March 1990 Dollars 2.6bn in the private funds of
Sheikh Zayed and Crown Prince Khalifa of Abu Dhabi was entrusted to BCCI, at
the instigation of Mr Hasan Abedi, the founder of the bank.
The money was invested in account 20071 in ICIC in regular instalments
throughout the decade, then distributed to dozens of sub-accounts in BCCI
branches around the world.
About Dollars 600m went to prop up the Gulf Group, a Pakistan-based shipping
conglomerate with delinquent loans, and Dollars 1bn in the purchase of BCCI
shares and notes. The rest went to support other failed loans, and the
bank's Treasury division, which lost more than Dollars 1.8bn in 1980-87.
An elaborate system of dual accounting developed, by which the bank would
spend the money and then prepare regular falsified valuation statements
showing how the funds were supposedly being invested and earning interest.
By 1989 BCCI was telling Abu Dhabi that the portfolio was worth Dollars
4.3bn. But just Dollars 150m was left in the account when BCCI was closed in
July 1991 and the only other money returned to the government was Dollars
450m it requested back in 1988-89.
In an internal note in 1985 Mr Swaleh Naqvi, chief operating officer of the
bank, makes reference to a 'number of transactions we will not be able to
explain'. The funds typically moved along a tortuous route which made
tracing transactions difficult. Money was transferred through intermediaries
before being dispersed.
Only after four years of pressure from Abu Dhabi for an audit of its
portfolio did BCCI hire a small local firm to carry out the work in 1988.
The reports do not express any concerns about the recoverability of the
assets, and state that the valuations provided to Abu Dhabi show a 'true and
fair view'.
Abu Dhabi says it was only when the demands on BCCI dwarfed the remaining
funds in the portfolio in April 1990 that the misappropriation was
uncovered, when Mr Naqvi confessed and sought new funds. Abu Dhabi then
began an investigation.
</TEXT>
