<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / N Sea oil output boosted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The steady rise in North Sea oil and gas production - which has been a big
factor behind falling international oil prices - will be boosted this week
when the East Brae field off Scotland comes on-stream.
The first oil should flow today or tomorrow, according to Marathon Oil,
operator of the field. East Brae has a capacity of 100,000 barrels a day,
although the initial production rate will be about 20,000 b/d. Investment in
the field totals Pounds 867m.
Output from the UK sector of the North Sea rose to 2.43m b/d in November,
compared with 2.13m b/d a year earlier. Production will rise even further
next year as new fields approach their peak production rates.
The prospects for further gas finds in Liverpool Bay received a boost
yesterday when Hamilton Oil, Lasmo and Monument Resources reported that an
exploratory well had struck gas in a block 3km (1.8 miles) from the Hamilton
gas field. Another well is expected to be drilled in the area.
The developers of the Liverpool Bay project, which received approval from
the government last month, have been confident of finding a number of
smaller oil and gas accumulations near the main fields.
</TEXT>
