<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / Deming, US quality control expert, dies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr W. Edwards Deming, the American quality control expert who became one of
the most influential figures in modern industrial management, died yesterday
peacefully in his sleep at his Washington, DC, home. He was 93.
Mr Deming, one of several US quality control experts who taught in Japan
after the second world war, playing a crucial role in revolutionising
Japanese manufacturing tech- niques and helping the country gain a leading
global position in many industries. Although he was revered in Japan, his
ideas were largely ignored in his native US until the 1980s, when they
contributed to the so-called Total Quality Management (TQM) movement which
has helped improve American industrial efficiency.
Trained as a statistician, Deming helped develop a theory of how management
could gather statistics on subtle variations in manufacturing levels as a
way to improve the quality of a company's output, and then expanded this
into a theory of management that stressed worker involvement.
Leading US companies yesterday expressed sorrow. General Motors said: 'In
our view there is no single person in the world that has had a more profound
effect on quality processes than did Dr Deming'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
</TP>
