<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 93 / French franc surges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French franc yesterday strengthened on the money markets to reach
FFr3.409 against the D-Mark, its highest level since last summer's European
currency crisis.
Yesterday's gains, which were fuelled by the D-Mark's weakness and the
announcement of a healthy current account surplus for France in September,
marked a continuation of the franc's recent strong performance which has
taken it back above its old floor rate of FFr3.4305 to the D-Mark before the
extension of the European exchange rate mechanism trading bands.
The Paris stock market also benefited from the announcement by the Finance
Ministry of a FFr9bn (Pounds 1.02bn) current account surplus for September
and of a FFr56.53bn surplus for the first nine months of the year (against
FFr4.02bn for the same period of 1992). The CAC-40 Index rose by 1.23 per
cent during the day to close at 2,223.47.
Economists said that investors' sentiment towards France had improved in
recent weeks, reflecting cautious confidence in its recovery potential and
relief at the successful outcome of the Gatt negotiations. However, they
said the franc and French equities had also benefited from technical
adjustments as investors have tried to balance their investment positions
before the end of the year.
'The surge of interest in France is part of a general interest in European
investments,' said Mr Christopher Potts, chief French economist at Banque
Indosuez in Paris.
'But it's also fair to say that the franc has been helped by the gradual
realisation among investors that the Balladur government really is committed
to maintaining stability with the D-Mark.'
The mood of cautious confidence was reinforced by the publication of the
latest economic forecast from the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and
Development, which predicted a modest recovery for the French economy in
1994, with growth of 1.1 per cent in gross domestic product.
However, the OECD warned of a further increase in unemployment from its
present record of 12 per cent of the French workforce to 12.5 per cent
during 1994.
It does not expect to see the unemployment rate fall until 1995, when it
forecasts GDP growth of 2.7 per cent for France.
</TEXT>
