<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 93 / LWT presses on with ITV quartet plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London Weekend Television is pushing ahead with a plan to create a quartet
of ITV licences under combined ownership, as part of its defence against
Granada Group's hostile bid.
Only a passing mention is made of the plan in the letter and defence
document sent to shareholders yesterday by Sir Christopher Bland, LWT
chairman. The documents concentrate on LWT's record and prospects, adding
merely that it is in preliminary discussions with Yorkshire-Tyne Tees. There
is an undertaking that any proposals would be put to shareholders for
approval.
Despite City scepticism, talks that might see LWT making an agreed bid for
Yorkshire, and Anglia Television taking over Tyne Tees, appear to be making
progress. Apart from the possibility of creating the largest ITV company, if
the rules were changed to allow it, more immediate agreements are being
pursued.
These envisage LWT, Yorkshire, Tyne Tees and Anglia co-operating on
everything from cost reduction and programme production to advertising
sales.
LWT, as a 14 per cent shareholder in Yorkshire-Tyne Tees, has access to all
board papers and reckons the loss-making company's problems are being dealt
with. Senior executives clearly believe further significant savings can be
made at Yorkshire-Tyne Tees, a company in which Pearson, owner of the
Financial Times, has a stake.
Sir Christopher said yesterday: 'The LWT management have done well for
shareholders and themselves. They can do better and as it happens they like
working together as a team. They don't want to bale out now.' LWT management
holds around 10 per cent of the company.
LWT defence, page 16
</TEXT>
