<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 93 / Accountancy board divided on changes to handling of goodwill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Accounting Standards Board will today unveil two alternative proposals
for the treatment of goodwill in companies' accounts after its own members
were unable to agree a common line on one of the most controversial issues
in accounting.
Goodwill is the difference between what a company pays to acquire another
business and the value of the net assets of the company acquired. It
measures intangible assets, such as customers' goodwill, which are being
acquired. But some companies have used goodwill in an attempt to disguise
the high price they have paid for an acquisition.
The board's eight members were equally divided between allowing companies to
put goodwill into a special reserve, or hold it on the balance sheet and
write it off as its value diminishes over time. Mr David Tweedie, the
board's chairman, said yesterday that if no agreement emerged he planned to
hold open hearings to resolve the issue.
This approach would mark a significant shift from the way the board usually
makes decisions, through consensus and behind closed doors. When the board
debates the topic again next year, two members will have changed. The
selection of their replacements will be influential in determining the
outcome.
The board acknowledges that goodwill is an accounting anomaly and that there
is no complete solution for the way it can be treated. Current practice in
the UK is out of line with the rest of the world, which requires goodwill to
be written off over a number of years.
The board proposes six options, but will recommend two:
Goodwill should be capitalised on a company's balance sheet and amortised
over a fixed period of probably 20 years. If the goodwill has a longer
economic life, it should be amortised in accordance with an annually
reviewed procedure. Goodwill could be transferred to a separate reserve
immediately a company is acquired and its value assessed annually.
The paper says that intangible assets, such as brands and patents, should be
subsumed within purchased goodwill and not treated separately. Comments on
the paper are due before April 30. This should lead to more detailed
proposals in the autumn.
Accounting for Goodwill. Discussion Paper. Accountancy Books, PO Box 620,
Central Milton Keynes. MK9 2JX. Pounds 6
Accounts plan 'will reform' Whitehall, Page 7
See Lex
</TEXT>
