<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 93 / Accounts plan 'will reform Whitehall'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Changes to public-sector accounting practices in last month's Budget may be
one of the government's most important Whitehall management reforms, the
Social Market Foundation says today.
The foundation, an independent think-tank, says that insufficient attention
has been given to a Budget comment by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
calling for a move to 'resource accounting'.
At present most public-sector organisations formally account for the flow of
cash for their regular operations. But there is little accounting of the use
of capital to meet the costs of maintaining resources such as land,
buildings and large equipment, or of the extent to which these items might
have depreciated.
Mr Evan Davis, the report's author, says the introduction of such accounting
in the public sector would rank alongside market testing, the introduction
of executive agencies and the private finance initiative in its impact on
the restructuring of Whitehall. He says that the move would make it easier
to reveal the full costs of delivering services. The cost of a capital item
would not, for example, be carried on the day it was bought, but would be
spread through accounts as though the item were leased.
Another consequence would be to encourage the private sector to compete for
the provision of public services.
Mr Davis says that the private sector cannot easily compete in the provision
of capital goods to the state because Whitehall disburses grants for capital
in a broadly discretionary way.
But he says that the introduction of resource accounting would 'sort out the
problem of capital so that it does not have to be given out free of charge
in big occasional blocks to lucky recipients'.
The Importance of Resource Accounting. Social Market Foundation, 20 Queen
Anne's Gate, London SW1H 9AA.
</TEXT>
