<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 93 / Names to be given 10-year help on losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Names on the Lloyd's of London insurance market facing substantial losses
may soon be extended a long-term lifeline to help them meet the crippling
demands on their assets, it emerged yesterday.
Mr Ken Randall, chief executive of Randall Group, the insurance adviser,
said that he was close to announcing details of a financing package that
would allow repayment of losses over 10 years by Names - the individuals
whose assets have traditionally supported the market.
The service is one of a number of initiatives being planned by Randall Group
following the announcement yesterday that it had sold a substantial minority
stake to JO Hambro Magan, the merchant bank.
Mr Randall said he had obtained the support of one US and several UK banks
towards raising on the Euro-markets at least 'a few hundreds of millions'
and possibly more than a billion pounds, which would be used to pay cash
calls levied on Names.
The package would be structured so that Names would pay only interest on
their loans for the first three years, then equal-sized instalments of the
capital over seven to 10 years.
The announcement could provide welcome relief to many Names considering
whether to accept a Pounds 900m out-of-court legal settlement with Lloyd's
or pursue litigation.
The latest estimates from Chatset, the research group, suggest that Names
could face demands for Pounds 8.65bn over the next 20 years.
Mr Randall said he had been working on the idea over a number of weeks and
had held detailed discussions 'at a very high level' in Lloyd's. He said he
was close to resolving a number of 'technical hurdles'.
He said that the idea had already been tested, and final arrangements were
being made. Names would be approved for the scheme on a case-by-case basis.
The idea has been supported with help from Magan, which yesterday announced
that it had bought 49 per cent of the shares in Randall Group for an
undisclosed sum.
The group will in the future concentrate on three areas: insurance
consultancy and management, investment management of insurance funds, and
introductory and advisory services for investors in the London market.
Mr Randall, a former head of regulation at Lloyd's, refused to provide
details of the financial position of the company other than to say that its
annual turnover was several million pounds.
