<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 93 / Jaguar boosts output by 43%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Jaguar has increased output by 43 per cent this year to about 29,500 cars
from last year's 20,593. The 1992 figure was the lowest for 11 years.
Following the cut of about 45 per cent in its UK workforce in 1991 and last
year the fortunes of Jaguar, a subsidiary of Ford of the US, have improved
markedly. Its UK workforce has been virtually unchanged at about 6,450.
In contrast to much of the European car industry it has avoided short-time
working this year and since August it has had significant overtime at its
Coventry plants.
Its worldwide retail sales have risen by about 24 per cent this year to
between 27,500 and 28,000 from 22,475 last year, largely due to a rising US
demand.
Jaguar more than doubled its sales in the US in November to 1,356 from 616
in the same month a year ago, with about 70 per cent of its US business now
based on leasing. The US is Jaguar's single most important market worldwide
and its sales there increased 49 per cent in the first 11 months of the year
to 11,358.
The luxury carmaker has been in loss for five years in succession from 1989
to 1993, but the losses have been reduced significantly in recent months.
Its operating losses in the first nine months of the year fell to Dollars
226m (Pounds 151.6m) from Dollars 300m in the same period a year earlier.
Losses in the third quarter were reduced to Dollars 108m from Dollars 135m,
but the third-quarter loss this year included a one-off charge of Dollars
65m for the closure of Venture Pressings, its joint venture with GKN.
Jaguar is being increasingly integrated into Ford's European operations and
next year production of the stamped body panels for Jaguar cars will be
transferred from Venture Pressings to the Ford plant at Halewood,
Merseyside, which has spare capacity.
