FT  20 DEC 93 / Security alert disrupts London trains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Several main-line stations in London were closed yesterday and services in
Kent were disrupted after a security alert, Conner Middelmann writes.
Investigations centred on the line to London from Sevenoaks, but nothing was
found in searches lasting most of the day.
The stations reopened in the afternoon but Network SouthEast said it was too
early to say whether service would be back to normal for this morning's rush
hour.
'We would advise people to listen in to their local radio stations to find
out what the latest situation is,' a spokesman said.
Network SouthEast said a caller using a recognised IRA code word telephoned
at about 4.30am yesterday, prompting the closure of dozens of stations in
the the south-eastern division. Buses were used to ferry passengers from
outlying stations to central London.
A bomb exploded on a Network SouthEast line near Woking, Surrey, last
Tuesday, and two unexploded devices were found at nearby Brookwood station
on Thursday.
