<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 93 / Milosevic may have to form coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Socialists of Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic last night were
leading parliamentary elections by a narrow margin as Serbia voted amid
economic collapse.
But early, unofficial results suggested that the Socialists were unlikely to
win a majority of the 250-seat parliament and would be forced to form a
coalition government. Full unofficial results are expected today.
While Mr Milosevic was not facing re-election, the poll was seen as a
crucial test of whether he could keep his hold over Serbia, with inflation
running at a monthly rate of 45,000 per cent. A spokesman for the Socialists
said Mr Milosevic's party was headed for victory throughout Serbia.
By contrast, leaders of DEPOS, the opposition coalition, and the centrist
Democratic party, last night claimed a strong showing in Belgrade and in
other Serbian towns, winning more than 30 per cent of the votes counted,
according to partial results.
As he cast his ballot yesterday. Mr Milosevic said: 'I am expecting
successful elections and a stable government.' However, if the initial
results are borne out, the poll will fail to deliver the Serbian president a
compliant government. He called the early elections, Serbia's third in four
years, after ultra-nationalist allies threatened to bring down his Socialist
government.
Officials said more than 50 per cent of Serbia's 7m voters had turned out
for the poll.
