<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 93 / ANC takes step towards agreeing to Afrikaner homeland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The African National Congress and South Africa's white right-wing groups
have reached agreement in principle to establish a 'homeland' for
Afrikaners, a significant symbolic concession to rightwing whites who fear
black majority rule.
The agreement, which has not yet been made public, is due to be signed
tomorrow in Johannesburg. It is understood to be hedged with conditions and
is only a first step to a firm deal.
No agreement appears to have been reached on important questions such as the
borders of the proposed homeland, whether blacks living in it would be
allowed to vote, and the powers of the homeland government.
But the accord has important symbolic value, and illustrates the ANC's
commitment to persuading rightwing whites to contest next year's all-race
elections.
In the agreement, the Afrikaner Volksfront (Afrikaner People's Front), the
umbrella group which represents most right-wing Afrikaners, commits itself
to participate in the poll if detailed agreement on a homeland is reached
early next year.
The two sides will now enter intensive talks designed to meet the timetable
for detailed agreements in January and February.
Difficult negotiations lie ahead over what the term 'volkstaat' (people's
state, or homeland) will mean. It is highly unlikely that an independent
ethnic state such as Israel could be created for the Afrikaners because
there is no substantial area where they are in the majority, and little
likelihood that large numbers would move to a newly-created state.
Instead, the 'volkstaat' could consist of small areas, sub-regions within
the country's provinces, where Afrikaners could exercise some autonomy.
Asked to define the degree of autonomy required in a volkstaat, one AVF
representative said: 'If emotionally the people feel they are governing
themselves, that would be a volkstaat. Language would be a huge thing.'
Control over education would also be important. The Swiss cantonal system,
studied by a joint ANC-AVF delegation, may be used as a model.
But the AVF is not a monolith and hard right groups are holding out for a
more powerful ethnic state. The radical leader of the white-supremacist
Conservative Party, Mr Ferdi Hartzenberg, is understood to support
tomorrow's accord, but reaching detailed agreement with him could prove
difficult.
Mr Nelson Mandela, the ANC leader, has been strongly against demands for an
Afrikaner homeland, although he has said significant power could be devolved
to Afrikaner areas. 'Sure, we've got a long way to go,' said one AVF
official. 'But when we started, it was only a dream.'
Negotiators from the government, the ANC and the right-wing Freedom Alliance
were to meet this morning in last-ditch attempts to agree on constitutional
amendments before the new constitution passes through parliament on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
</CN>
